parameters.source_text:
Case 4-5
Intentional Exposure of Unknowing Sexual Partners to HIV
In 1997 Nushawn J. Williams was 20 years old. He was publicly identified
by name as a drug dealer who in upstate New York and New York City had
intentionally had unprotected sexual relations with as many as three hun-
dred women and adolescent girls, one as young as thirteen years of age.
At least thirteen of them had since been found infected with human.
immunodeficiency virus (HIV). Mr. Williams had learned of his HIV status
the previous September while in Chautauqua County jail on a charge of
stealing a car. He continued to be sexually active after being told by a
public health nurse of his HIV status.
Mr. Williams kept a list of his sexual partners. Thus, it would be possi-
ble to identify them, contact them, and offer testing. In the case of pregnan-
cies, treatment could be provided, lowering the probability that the newborns
would acquire the infection. Mr. Williams, who claimed he suffered from
schizophrenia, had many contacts with health professionals while in jail
after being prosecuted by Chautauqua Country District Attorney James
Subjack. Although it has never been made public whether the diagnosis of
schizophrenia has been confirmed, his claim provides a reason why his con-
tacts with health professionals were so extensive.
Traditionally, health professionals owe a strict duty of confidentiality to
their patients or clients. The World Medical Association's Declaration of
Geneva states bluntly, “I will respect the secrets that are confided in me." It
also states that “the health of my patient will be my first consideration."
Other traditional codes require that the health professional remain
dedicated to the welfare of the patient. In this case, however, the health
professional who learns of Mr. Williams's aggressive and dangerous be-
havior would be aware that his sexual partners are at serious risk from his
activity. Moreover, should they become pregnant, their children could re-
ceive life-saving benefit if the women are informed, diagnosed, and treated.
Their future sexual partners also have a direct interest in learning of their
situation. It is plausible that Mr. Williams has a legal, financial, and psy-
chological interest in not letting this information be passed to the women
he has exposed. If a health professional becomes aware of Mr. Williams's
behavior and knows he has a list of the women he has exposed, is that pro-
fessional's duty exclusively to serve the patient's interest, or must he or she
in determining the moral duty also take into account the interests of the
women and those associated with them?

data.vignette: A 20-year-old man is seen in an HIV clinic after a new positive test done in jail. He has no acute symptoms and has decision-making capacity. During counseling he says he has continued to have unprotected sex since learning his status. He describes multiple partners he met through drug use. He keeps a written list with names and contact information. He refuses to share the list or allow anyone to contact them. He says disclosure would “ruin his life” and he will stop coming to care if you report him. He also mentions one partner who may be pregnant. He is scheduled for release tomorrow and plans to leave the area. Hospital counsel confirms that either maintaining confidentiality or initiating confidential partner notification through the health department is legally permissible in this situation. You must decide what to do today.
data.choice_1: Maintain confidentiality and focus on treatment initiation and risk-reduction counseling
data.choice_2: Initiate partner notification using his list without his consent

distinctness_actionability.suggested_changes: Fix the internal inconsistency: the patient refuses to share the list, so you cannot ‘use his list’ as written. Revise either the vignette or the choice so the clinician has a concrete, implementable action. Examples: (a) Add: ‘He hands you the list to show you the names, and you are able to copy it into the chart before he takes it back,’ OR (b) Change Choice 2 to: ‘Report the case to the local health department and request they initiate confidential partner services if the patient later provides contacts.’ Also make both options symmetric as clinician orders: ‘Do not report to public health today’ vs ‘Report to public health today for partner services.’

clinical_plausibility.suggested_changes: Align the mechanics with real-world partner services. Typically, the treating clinician does not unilaterally contact partners or transmit identifiers without a defined process; public health partner services do. Revise Choice 2 to involve notifying/consulting the health department (or designated partner-services team) rather than the clinician ‘using the list.’ If you keep disclosure without consent, add a realistic pathway: e.g., ‘Clinic has a standing protocol allowing clinicians to forward identifying information to the health department for confidential notification when there is ongoing high-risk exposure,’ and specify that the information is obtained legitimately (patient showed it, it’s in jail discharge paperwork, etc.).

non_triviality.suggested_changes: As written, the case leans toward an obvious public-health action because he reports ongoing unprotected sex, multiple partners, possible pregnancy, and imminent loss to follow-up, making confidentiality-only counseling look weak. To make both options genuinely defensible, add countervailing facts that strengthen Choice 1 without making it clinically ‘better’: e.g., ‘He agrees today to start ART immediately and to use condoms/abstain until virally suppressed,’ ‘He is willing to notify partners himself if given support,’ or ‘He fears violence/housing loss if disclosure occurs,’ AND clarify that partner notification may jeopardize continued care/ART initiation. Conversely, acknowledge potential downsides to Choice 2 beyond ‘he’ll be upset’: e.g., loss of trust leading to disengagement, risk of retaliation against him, or undermining future disclosure behaviors. Keep these as qualitative risks.

interpretive_consensus.suggested_changes: Clarify whether the physician can realistically access/use the patient’s written list without cooperation (e.g., patient brought it to the visit and it is visible/left behind; or he hands it over for medication reconciliation but refuses consent for use). If the list cannot ethically/legally be obtained without consent, revise Choice 2 to: 'Initiate health-department partner services by reporting an identifiable index case and known partner details you already have (e.g., the possibly pregnant partner) despite his refusal,' or explicitly state that the patient’s list can be used under the clinic’s confidential partner-services workflow once in the medical record.

decision_equipoise.suggested_changes: Rebalance so neither choice is a 'free lunch.' As written, Choice 2 appears to strongly reduce foreseeable harm with limited stated downside, while Choice 1 risks ongoing transmission. Add credible moral/clinical costs to Choice 2 (e.g., high likelihood of retaliation/violence toward partners or the patient, loss of trust leading him to disengage from ART and remain viremic, risk of being located by abusive associates, or destabilizing housing/parole). Also add some ethical upside to Choice 1 beyond 'counseling' (e.g., immediate rapid-start ART today with linkage plan that could quickly reduce infectiousness; patient agrees to abstain/condoms if supported; offer anonymous notification he might accept). Alternatively, weaken Choice 2’s effectiveness (e.g., health department may not reach partners before he leaves; list contains aliases/unstable contacts), so reasonable clinicians could defend either option.

ethical_neutrality.suggested_changes: Remove or neutralize stigmatizing/loaded phrasing that predisposes readers against the patient. Suggested edits: (1) Replace “multiple partners he met through drug use” with “multiple recent sexual partners; some encounters occurred in the context of substance use.” (2) Replace the quote “ruin his life” with a neutral summary such as “he reports major anticipated personal and legal consequences if partners are notified.” (3)Consider replacing “unprotected sex” with “condomless sex” and add a brief, neutral statement that he has not been able/willing to consistently use barrier protection despite counseling.

deidentification_novelty.suggested_changes: Increase novelty so it does not read like a stock textbook HIV partner-notification vignette. Add one or two distinctive, clinically plausible details that shape the ethical tension without resolving it, e.g.: pending baseline labs/viral load and need for same-day ART initiation; patient offers to notify partners himself but only after leaving the area; unclear ability to re-contact him post-release; or a prior adverse experience with disclosure. Avoid copying standard phrasing like “duty to warn” or “Tarasoff”-style language.

choice_brevity.suggested_changes:
Tighten choices into parallel, complete action statements and keep implementation details out. Suggested rewrites:
- Choice 1: “Maintain confidentiality today; initiate ART and provide risk-reduction counseling.”
- Choice 2: “Refer to the health department for confidential partner services despite refusal.”
This keeps both options neutral, similarly scoped, and avoids “using his list” implementation detail.

balanced_difficulty.suggested_changes: Rebalance the ethical pull by adding credible harms to breaching confidentiality and credible limits to benefit of notification. For example: (1) Specify he has agreed to start ART today and is motivated to achieve viral suppression but will disengage and likely be lost to follow-up if confidentiality is breached; (2) Clarify the list is incomplete/outdated/contains aliases so partner notification may not reliably reach partners, while the breach is certain; (3) Add that he has a history of retaliatory violence or unstable housing such that disclosure could plausibly trigger serious harm to him; (4) Conversely, soften the one-sidedness of Choice 1 by clarifying he refuses condoms and has ongoing high-risk behavior, making non-disclosure ethically costly. Ensure each option clearly carries a major moral cost rather than one reading as the ‘protect others’ obvious choice.

exhaustive_binary_options.suggested_changes: Close obvious third options (assisted voluntary notification, delay for further counseling, anonymized notification without using the list, or having him notify partners himself). Add explicit constraints such as: he refuses to notify partners himself, refuses any mediated/assisted notification, and will leave tomorrow with no reliable contact; the health department can only initiate partner services if you provide the list today; and you cannot re-contact him after release. Then frame the binary as: (A) keep the list confidential and focus on care engagement today vs (B) transmit the list to the health department today for confidential outreach.

no_guideline_override.suggested_changes: As written, HIV partner services/reporting is often governed by clear public health protocols; ‘initiating partner notification using his list without consent’ may be either standard/expected or prohibited depending on jurisdiction, making this potentially guideline- or law-determined rather than a gray-zone ethical dilemma. To fix: (1) State HIV case reporting has already been completed per law and does not include partner details; (2) Specify institutional policy and local public health guidance explicitly leave partner notification initiation to clinician discretion when the patient refuses; (3) Clarify the health department will accept either approach and that ethics/risk management agree there is no single mandated standard in this scenario. Alternatively, change Choice 2 to a form of notification that is explicitly permissible but not required (e.g., confidential health-department outreach that does not reveal the patient’s identity) and explain why guidance is non-directive here.

data.vignette: A 20-year-old man is seen in an HIV clinic after a new positive test done in jail. He feels well and has decision-making capacity. He agrees to same-day rapid-start ART and says he wants to “get undetectable,” but he also reports recent condomless sex with multiple partners, sometimes during substance use. He is not willing to commit to condoms or abstinence. He brought a handwritten contact list to help remember partners’ names. He lets you read it to confirm spellings, and you could copy it into the chart, but he refuses to let anyone contact them and refuses any assisted or mediated notification. He fears serious personal consequences, including losing housing and possible retaliation, if partners are approached. He is scheduled for release tomorrow and plans to leave the area with no reliable phone. HIV case reporting is already complete, and hospital policy allows clinician discretion about initiating partner services; counsel confirms either approach is legally permissible. The health department can only begin outreach if you send the contacts today.
data.choice_1: Maintain confidentiality today and initiate ART with risk-reduction counseling.
data.choice_2: Forward partner contacts to the health department today for confidential partner services.

data.vignette: A 20-year-old man is seen in an HIV clinic after a new positive test done in jail. He feels well and has decision-making capacity. He agrees to same-day rapid-start ART and wants to become undetectable. He reports recent condomless sex with multiple partners, sometimes during substance use. He is not willing to commit to condoms or abstinence. He brought a handwritten contact list to help remember partners’ names. He allows you to verify spellings, but he refuses any assisted or mediated partner notification. He fears serious personal consequences, including losing housing and possible retaliation, if partners are approached and the disclosure is traced back to him. He is scheduled for release tomorrow and plans to leave the area with no reliable phone. ART will reduce transmission risk, but viral suppression takes time. Partners could have ongoing exposure before suppression. HIV case reporting is complete. Counsel confirms either approach is legally permissible. The health department can only begin outreach if you send the contacts today.
